SIMPLE: pervert
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pervert
<hw>Per*vert"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Perverted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Perverting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>pervertir</ets>, L.
<ets>pervertere</ets>, <ets>perversum</ets>; <ets>per</ets> +
<ets>vertere</ets> to turn. See <er>Per-</er>, and
<er>Verse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn another way; to
divert.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let's follow him, and <qex>pervert</qex> the present wrath.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To turn from truth, rectitude, or propriety; to
divert from a right use, end, or way; to lead astray; to corrupt; also,
to misapply; to misinterpret intentionally; <as>as, to <ex>pervert</ex>
one's words</as>.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He, in the serpent, had <qex>perverted</qex> Eve.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pervert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pervert
<hw>Per*vert"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become perverted; to take
the wrong course.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Testament of
Love.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pervert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pervert
<hw>Per"vert</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who has been
perverted; one who has turned to error, especially in religion; --
opposed to <contr>convert</contr>. See the Synonym of
<er>Convert</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That notorious <qex>pervert</qex>, Henry of Navarre.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perverter</ent>⟦br⟧
